High rates of abortion in Antigua and Barbuda

“Now the incidents of abortions are, depending on the source … it can go as high as 70 abortions in a year, in Antigua,’’ Akinyi Farndon said when on January 4, the Ministry of Health on St. Johns launched three new training programmes specially designed for nurses and medical professionals in the country, as part of its community outreach programme.

Hitting back at the belief that the number of abortions in Antigua is low, Akinyi Farndon said that the issue is one that is “really complex’‘.

She said that while people would tell you that the number is small, “that is the impact of the increase in abortions that occurs in any given community’’.

She also observed that the problem of teenage pregnancies and unsafe abortions increases as population reduces due to low birthrate or natural deaths.

Meanwhile, Akinyi Farndon opined that the continuation of the argument about the legality or illegality of abortion creates a large market where unsafe and illegal procedures are being carried out by certain professionals.

“We don’t have enough to cover the number of procedures that are actually available by law, so, what happens is you have now a market for unsafe procedure and criminal activity,” the security expert explained.
